Cost and pricing: MCP vs CLI

The biggest cost in most AI systems isn’t infrastructure—it’s tokens. Every request you send to a model (input + output) costs money, and that adds up fast. Engineering time is the other major factor, but usually secondary.

MCP cost model
High upfront token cost

MCP works by loading tool schemas into the model’s context. That sounds neat, but it’s expensive.

In practice, this can take anywhere from ~20k to 150k+ tokens per session. In some setups, most of the context window is already used before the user even does anything.

So you’re paying a significant amount just to describe what tools exist.

Costs grow quickly in agent loops

Most AI agents follow a loop like:

plan → call tool → observe → repeat

With MCP, every step carries structured messages and tool definitions along with it. As the workflow gets longer, the context grows, and each step becomes more expensive than the last.

This is where costs can really spiral.

Where MCP saves money

MCP can still make sense at scale.

Because everything is structured:

integrations are more standardized
parsing errors are reduced
tools are easier to reuse across teams

So while token costs are higher, engineering effort can go down over time.

Inefficiency in practice

A common issue: systems load a lot of tools that never get used.

For example, you might expose 50–100 tools, but only a handful are actually called. The rest still sit in the context, consuming tokens for no reason.

That’s wasted spend.

CLI cost model
Much lower token usage

CLI-based approaches are lean. You’re typically sending:

a command
maybe some context
and then reading the output

This usually stays in the range of a few hundred to a few thousand tokens per step, which is significantly cheaper than MCP-heavy setups.

In many cases, this leads to 10x+ savings.

More efficient in loops

In the same agent loop:

plan → run command → read output → repeat

you’re only passing what’s needed each time. There’s no schema overhead being dragged along.

Costs scale more predictably and stay relatively low.

Better use of tokens

With CLI, tokens are mostly spent on:

actual reasoning
actual outputs

not on describing tools or formats.

So you get more value per token.

Where CLI becomes expensive

The tradeoff shows up in engineering effort.

You’ll likely need to:

parse unstructured outputs
write glue code between tools
handle edge cases and failures manually

This takes time and adds maintenance overhead.

Safety and infra costs

Letting an AI run commands directly isn’t safe by default.

You’ll need:

sandboxing
permission controls
monitoring

That adds extra engineering and infrastructure work.

Side-by-side summary
Token costs
MCP: high upfront cost, grows quickly with longer workflows
CLI: low overhead, scales more predictably

In many real setups, CLI can reduce token spend by 60–90%.

Engineering costs
MCP: more effort upfront, easier to maintain later
CLI: quick to start, but can get messy over time
Infra and operations
MCP: more structured, easier to secure and standardize
CLI: more flexible, but you have to build safety and reliability yourself
The tradeoff
MCP: higher token costs, lower engineering cost at scale
CLI: lower token costs, higher engineering and safety overhead
Why many startups prefer CLI

Early-stage teams usually care about:

reducing API spend
moving quickly

So they optimize for lower token usage, even if it means more manual engineering.

That’s why CLI-heavy approaches are common in prototypes and early products. MCP tends to come in later, if and when things need to scale.

What most teams end up doing

A mix of both:

CLI for execution (cheap, flexible)
MCP or similar structure for:
external APIs
sensitive operations
shared systems across teams
Bottom line

MCP is better when you’re optimizing for long-term structure and team scalability.

CLI is better when you’re trying to keep costs down and move fast.

Right now, since token costs are still a major constraint, a lot of teams are leaning toward CLI-first approaches.
